WEBVTT

00:02.647 --> 00:16.650
This is an interview with Colonel Herbert L. 
Curry, United States Marine Corps, by Brian W.

00:02.647 --> 00:16.650
Icarus on April 29, 1989, at the Trigon Building, 
Texas A&M University, College Station, Texas,

00:02.647 --> 00:16.650
concerning the Vietnam War. In the interest of 
accumulating knowledge about the war, I am going

00:17.332 --> 00:25.986
to donate this tape to Texas A&M Oral History 
Collection in the University Archives. Is that

00:26.006 --> 00:27.028
all right with you, sir? Yes, sir. Sir, you had 
previously stated in the interview given by James

00:29.849 --> 00:44.986
W. Hodges, Jr. on November 29, 1988, that your 
first experience in Vietnam in 1963 was with the

00:29.849 --> 00:44.986
3rd Recon Battalion and the underwater 
demolition teams of the Navy. It has been stated by

00:45.687 --> 00:53.676
other sources that during these years, even the 
special warfare units had difficulties

00:45.687 --> 00:53.676
performing. Would you please expand on that, sir? 
Yes, I will. First,

00:59.566 --> 01:13.046
under the conditions that I was operating, we 
didn't have difficulties before me, at least not

00:59.566 --> 01:13.046
difficulties with the South Vietnamese. We 
operated from the board ship on a daily basis. The

01:18.014 --> 01:28.189
underwater demolition folks conducted 
hydrographic surveys from the high water mark of

01:18.014 --> 01:28.189
the beach out to the sea. or possible landing sites 
or landing beaches my platoon and i conducted

01:28.625 --> 01:56.083
reconnaissance from the high water mark of the 
beach up to 10 miles inward we would go in select

01:28.625 --> 01:56.083
routes of egress determine trafficability away 
from the beach select terrain objectives recon

01:28.625 --> 01:56.083
towns villages airfields any type of military 
that was placed in that area. The only difficulty

02:01.351 --> 02:08.882
that we encountered was that there would be 
Vietnamese in the area, Vietnamese military in

02:01.351 --> 02:08.882
the area. They were unaware that we were operating 
in there at the same time. There was not a

02:13.409 --> 02:18.797
communications set up between the ship that I was 
operating from and the local Vietnamese military

02:19.621 --> 02:22.504
forces ashore. So we were operating 
independently, and sometimes we would have a

02:23.025 --> 02:34.036
chance meeting with Vietnamese, and they weren't 
aware that we were in the area. On one occasion, I

02:34.056 --> 02:48.632
was on a road about five or six miles inland, and 
coming around at the end was a military jeep with an

02:34.056 --> 02:48.632
army Vietnamese captain. stopped and said, hey, 
we've got a big battle going on just around the

02:49.068 --> 02:54.357
curve and over that hill. And we had no knowledge of 
that, so we had no intelligence.

03:00.007 --> 03:07.359
And Vietnam was in a war at that time, and yet the US 
forces were in there operating. So did I have

03:07.379 --> 03:08.642
trouble operating? No, I didn't, because I was 
operating from sea on a daily basis. My logistical

03:15.798 --> 03:17.920
support was there. We were well taken care of. But 
as far as any interface with the Vietnamese, we

03:19.802 --> 03:33.175
didn't have that, nor did we have any intelligence 
being given to us about what the area was like or was

03:19.802 --> 03:33.175
there any enemy forces in the area at that time. I 
understand it's not the recon's mission to engage

03:33.195 --> 03:42.565
the enemy, but were there such encounters? Yes. We 
had a couple of encounters. One time we were in the

03:47.714 --> 04:03.074
Marble Mountain area, and we received some 
gunfire,

03:47.714 --> 04:03.074
and we immediately departed the area, got back to 
our rubber boats, and went out to sea. Another time

04:03.094 --> 04:10.543
we were in the Mekong Delta area, south of Vung Tau,

04:13.325 --> 04:17.330
Half of my platoon got pinned down for an excess of a 
day. We were drawn from the mangrove swamps. We

04:20.834 --> 04:32.890
were on the beach, and the tide was out, and the 
tidal flap was such, or the tidal range was such, or

04:20.834 --> 04:32.890
the beach gradient was such that we couldn't get 
boats in to evacuate the people. So we had to remain

04:32.910 --> 04:40.039
undercover throughout the day until the tide came 
in and we could evacuate the people. Yes, it was our

04:40.059 --> 04:42.842
mission not to engage We were strictly to have

04:43.092 --> 04:48.057
thousands of them. Sir, what were the basic 
differences between activities while you were a

04:48.077 --> 04:56.966
platoon commander of a recon unit and a company 
commander of an infantry unit? Which benefited

04:58.047 --> 05:00.329
you the most in dealing with the war?

05:05.374 --> 05:11.580
Well, I can't say that one benefited me more than 
the other. Because I had been in Vietnam as a second

05:12.353 --> 05:17.922
lieutenant, I knew something about the people. I 
knew what the country and the planet were like. And

05:20.586 --> 05:25.393
that gave me some first-hand knowledge on how to 
operate there. I came back several years later as a

05:25.413 --> 05:30.180
captain and a company commander. I had more 
experience at that time. Plus, I'd gone through

05:34.146 --> 05:39.154
three weeks of specialized Marine Corps training 
at Camp Hillary, California. which was to prepare

05:39.539 --> 05:42.943
people to go into Vietnam. We had courses on, 
classes on the culture of the people, the do's and

05:44.304 --> 05:57.318
don'ts, and how to react with people, because we 
were over there to win the hearts and minds, as well

05:44.304 --> 05:57.318
as to win military. We also had infiltration 
courses, courses that trained us in detecting and

05:57.338 --> 06:05.327
avoiding moving traps and mines.

06:09.982 --> 06:13.527
So I felt that I was pretty well-prepared when I 
went to Vietnam. Still, there is nothing like

06:13.547 --> 06:19.556
on-the-job experience in combat whenever you get 
over that. Nothing truly compares you for

06:19.717 --> 06:22.841
everything in combat. So when you're asking for a 
comparison between being a company commander in

06:23.803 --> 06:36.782
combat and being a platoon commander with 
reconnaissance equipment as a second

06:23.803 --> 06:36.782
lieutenant, there is no comparison. All right, so 
I guess that will kind of lead into my next question

06:37.758 --> 06:40.842
now. On your return to Vietnam in 1968, what were 
the noticeable differences then and your first

06:41.723 --> 06:51.795
experience in 1963? In 1963,

06:51.815 --> 06:57.402
I had gone in. One of the missions had gone in to the 
Bay Airfield. or the military air base there in the

07:02.969 --> 07:12.504
northern

07:02.969 --> 07:12.504
portion of South Vietnam. It was basically a 
sleepy village, oriental village. The airfield,

07:19.875 --> 07:28.369
although there was a war going on, was fairly 
enacted by the U.S.

07:28.389 --> 07:29.871
I was amazed when I flew in. in 1968, January of 
1968. As I recall, there had been another airstrip

07:35.539 --> 07:49.391
prepared parallel to

07:35.539 --> 07:49.391
the original airstrip.

07:49.411 --> 07:56.237
It was an air base in the city of Busting Rock City.

07:56.257 --> 07:59.740
I was really, I was amazed what America could do 
when it was mobilized

08:00.631 --> 08:12.661
and eventually made. We had rocket crushers, 
postal services, clubs, exchanges, large

08:12.681 --> 08:19.267
organizations, lots of jets flying in and out, 
coming in on those runways. The transformation

08:19.287 --> 08:23.270
was like day in, night out. Is there any different 
from what it was like in 1963, as in that you were

08:31.124 --> 08:32.486
located down in them. But I guess the real question 
I'm asking is the attitude in the people and, I

08:33.347 --> 08:43.079
guess, the change in the war atmosphere.

08:44.881 --> 08:53.331
I didn't have that much contact with the people in 
1968 and 1969. When I was there in 1963, the

08:53.351 --> 08:59.899
people still lived throughout the countryside. 
because the war was not at the intensity that it was

09:00.824 --> 09:07.071
in 68 and 69. But when I got there in 68, I found that 
we still had Vietnamese living in the name, and

09:07.091 --> 09:23.028
they were allowed to travel Route 1, but there were 
checkpoints that controlled their travel, and

09:07.091 --> 09:23.028
they all actively seized at nighttime. Around the 
name, people still lived in villages But we had had

09:29.140 --> 09:32.683
what we called the CAP program at that time. That 
was Combined Action. But we took a squad of Marines

09:34.325 --> 09:40.391
and had them living at each village to train them in 
self-defense. The people would work their bills

09:41.752 --> 09:53.523
and crops in the daytime, and then they would 
return to their village, and all movement would

09:41.752 --> 09:53.523
cease after dark. Anything we knew was considered 
hostile for those Vietnamese, US forces, as well

09:53.543 --> 09:57.207
as the the local forces, what we call the PLs, I 
guess that's the popular forces, that were

09:58.148 --> 10:04.234
defending their little village of Hamlet. Later 
on in the year, when I moved up to the northern

10:05.976 --> 10:26.978
I-Corps, in the area from Guaviette north and 
Guaviette west of the Laotian border, I found that

10:05.976 --> 10:26.978
there were no villagers or people living in 
villages. They had all been taken from the

10:30.076 --> 10:34.523
countryside and taken to resettlement areas. 
These are camps that the U.S., I guess in

10:35.764 --> 10:46.961
conjunction with the U.S. Army, had constructed 
where they relocated everyone and they lived

10:35.764 --> 10:46.961
there. They lived there until the war was over. So 
in Northern I-Corps, there was no local populace

10:50.126 --> 10:57.957
out in the countryside. If we saw anyone, he was 
hostile. He was considered the authority of the

11:02.016 --> 11:06.622
leaves. Did this have any conflict with such 
villages or groups of Indians such as the

11:06.642 --> 11:19.560
Montagnards who were really not active in the war? 
